To Doc:<br>
     Thanks for talking to me, you make a excellent point.  My view on passive reading comes from teaching day to day and seeing many children find their textbooks boring.  I have seen books that were uninformative and even incorrect.  Active discussion is very valid as well as reading the views of others.  The most important learning for most students comes from participation (in all its facets), which I believe is the point of this dialog, what makes it special.  We all learn by participating, not just reading.  I have stats that back up this way of thought.  Many people learn by participation.  This I know as a teacher, and this is why I try to use the textbook only as a foundation for varied exploration.<br>
Pruning a tree (if done carefully) can SOMETIMES help it grow stronger and produce more fruit-catch my drift?<br>
     Doc, you can count on me being here to the end of this site, which I hope never comes.  In fact I am trying to alert fellow teachers to the existence of this site.  My only motives are to keep this site the way it is.  PLEASE UNDERSTAND THAT MY SUGGESTIONS ARE JUST IDEAS TO SAVE THIS SITE.  I just flew them up the flag pole to see what people thought.  I have never seen another site like this and I want to do what I can to keep it.  Count on my support.  Thanks for listening to just another FNG.   
